1. For the first scenario, where \(r=6\%\), \(R=12\), and \(m=12\), we plug these values into the formula:

\begin{align*}
T_{\text{H}}&=\frac{\ln (2)}{\ln \left(1+\frac{0.06}{12}\right)} \\
&=\frac{\ln (2)}{\ln \left(1+\frac{1}{200}\right)} \\
&=\frac{\ln (2)}{\ln \left(1.005\right)} \\
&\approx 11.49 \text{ years}
\end{align*}

Thus, it takes approximately 11.49 years for the annuity to double with a 6% annual interest rate and monthly compounding.

2. For the second scenario, where \(r=12\%\), \(R=12\), and \(m=12\), we plug these values into the formula:

\begin{align*}
T_{\text{H}}&=\frac{\ln (2)}{\ln \left(1+\frac{0.12}{12}\right)} \\
&=\frac{\ln (2)}{\ln \left(1+\frac{1}{100}\right)} \\
&=\frac{\ln (2)}{\ln \left(1.01\right)} \\
&\approx 7.27 \text{ years}
\end{align*}

Thus, it takes approximately 7.27 years for the annuity to double with a 12% annual interest rate and monthly compounding.

In conclusion, the lower the interest rate, the more quickly the annuity will double in value due to the effect of compound interest. This illustrates the importance of choosing higher interest rates when making financial investments, such as starting a business or investing in retirement accounts.

